This means that the JavaScript event handlers on that particular website override your bindings to the "inspect element" key combination (Ctrl + Shift + I).

Here's a possible approach to resolve this issue.

### Using Browser Developer Tools Shortcut by Modifying Browser JavaScript

Add the following code to the website's script tag:

```JavaScript
window.addEventListener('keydown', function(e) {
    if (e.ctrlKey && e.shiftKey && e.keyCode == 73) { 
        let devtools = window.open("https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Tools");
    }
});
```

This code adds a keydown event listener to the browser's window object. When the combination of the Control, Shift, and I keys are pressed, it opens the developer tools URL in a new tab (or window).

Since the script is executed on the same page as the shortcut, it bypasses the website's JavaScript functionality and does not affect other websites.

### Using Browser Extensions

Another approach is to create a Chrome extension. Extensions can listen to browser events and override default behavior for key combinations.

1. Create a new extension project using an IDE like Visual Studio or simply write the script manually in a text file.

2. In the extension, use the following code in your background script, which runs on every page load:

```JavaScript
chrome.pageAction.onClicked.addListener({
    tab: {
        isLoading: false,
        url: 'https://mnsw.pro/'
    }
}, function(activeInfo) {
    var target = chrome.tabs.executeScript({
        code: 'window.open("https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Tools");'
    });
});
```

3. Download the script file generated by your IDE or text editor and upload it as a part of your Chrome extension project.

4. Configure your extension manifest file to allow scripts to add a page action for the specified URL and execute your injected script in the context of the `https://mnsw.pro/` page.

[Here's a minimalist, tutorial-style guide on how to create a Chrome Extension][1].

Once your extension is installed in Chrome and activated for the desired website, you'll see a new icon (the page action) on the tab. Clicking this icon will open the developer tools on the `https://mnsw.pro/` page.

Remember that Chrome extensions need to be signed and/or distributed via the Chrome Web Store to be used on websites, otherwise, they will not work.

